Rating: 4
I live in Central NJ where every June is blueberry picking season so of course I had a lot of frozen blueberries left over from 2004 season and not a clue on what to do with them. I made this cake for the 4th of July, 2005 and was praying the whole time that it would taste ok. Wow!! The cake came out great and tasted great! I got rave reviews from everyone who ate the cake that day! The blueberries were not the sweetest so it gave the cake a nice, slightly, tart flavor that meshed well with the lightly sweet cake. This cake was moist and delicious. I made the cake a day head and followed the advice of the reviewer from Monrivia, CA and added an extra ¼ cup of butter and an extra ¼ cup of buttermilk. I used whole cultured buttermilk and not low-fat or reduced-fat buttermilk because using low-fat or reduced-fat buttermilk would add water to the cake and I wanted this cake to be as moist as possible. Not that there is anything wrong with using low-fat or reduced-fat buttermilk but I knew it was going to be a full fat and a high carbohydrate barbeque, after all it was Independence Day. After I creamed the butter and buttermilk with the flat beater on my Kitchen Aid Stand Mixer, I used the balloon whisk to whip the ingredients. This added air to the batter thus making the cake lighter so that it would rise higher during baking. If you use Crisco shortening (not oil) to flour a non-stick Nordic Ware Bundt pan, you will have no trouble releasing the, cooled, cake from the pan. I will defiantly make this cake again!

