Rating: 4
Delicious! Would I make it again? I already have! I really love lemon, and after reading previous reviews, I decided to keep a bottle of lemon extract handy to add as needed. I ended up using almost 1&1/2 tsps of lemon extract, being a little generous with the vanilla, and omitting the orange peel. We loved it! It was exactly like a bundt cake version of a rich, irresistible blueberry muffin from a great bakery! Definitely a hit on Mother's Day. Very moist, rich, and neither too heavy or too light in texture (both regular and veganized versions). If you have a smaller 10-cup capacity bundt, 2/3 of the recipe fits with a little extra room to spare if you feel like adding extra berries (it was great with really big ones). VEGANS! This worked really well with Ener-G egg replacer, margarine, and a combo of 3 Tbsp vegan sour cream, 1&1/2 tsps lemon juice, and nondairy milk to equal 3/4 cup in place of the buttermilk. Or you could probably just use all soured nondairy milk instead of bothering with the veg sour cream--the sour cream just replaced the thickness of buttermilk, and I happened to have some already on hand.

Rating: 3
I made this for Mother's Day breakfast, and it was a huge hit. I didn't use the orange peel, and I used fresh berries, taking another reviewer's suggestion of coating them in flour first (I think the recipe needs 2.5 cups of berries). It's easier to spoon the thick batter into the pan (use baby loaf pans if you don't have a bundt pan) than to pour it. I served it with creme fraiche, which was a fabulous complement. Next time I might try making it with cranberries...

